<h1>LG Dryer Overheating — Why It Gets Too Hot and What Happens If You Ignore It</h1>

<p>An LG dryer that runs too hot — scorching clothes, shutting off mid-cycle, or displaying d80/d90/d95 codes — is almost always telling you the same thing: hot air can't get out fast enough. The exhaust vent is restricted, heat is building up inside the drum instead of being expelled, and the machine is either protecting itself by shutting down or continuing to run at dangerous temperatures. The exterior cabinet gets burning hot to touch, especially around the top and back panels. The laundry room temperature rises noticeably during operation. Synthetic fabrics can show heat damage or melting. We handle these calls across Los Angeles County, Orange County, and Ventura County — and in summer months across LA when ambient temperatures are high, an already compromised vent system can push a borderline situation into a real problem faster than people expect.</p>

<h2>Why Overheating Is Urgent — The Cascade</h2>
<p>LG dryers have a built-in safety device called the thermal fuse — a one-shot component that permanently blows when the dryer exceeds a safe temperature. Once it blows, the dryer either shuts down completely or loses all heat. There's no reset. It has to be replaced.</p>
<p>The cascade looks like this: clogged vent → dryer overheats → thermal fuse blows → dryer stops heating → customer calls us thinking they have a heating problem when the real problem started weeks earlier with a vent blockage. We see this sequence constantly in Torrance and Long Beach. Catching overheating before the thermal fuse blows saves you a repair visit and keeps the dryer running. Beyond the fuse, sustained overheating stresses the heating element, cycling thermostat, and control board. Machines that run hot for extended periods fail more components over time.</p>

<h2>The Most Likely Causes</h2>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    1. Clogged Exhaust Vent
    <span class="sev-badge sev-high">Cause of 60% of overheating calls</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">d80 / d90 / d95 error codes</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Cabinet hot to touch top and back</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Laundry room gets humid while running</div>
  </div>
  <p>The exhaust vent is the only way hot moist air leaves the drum. When it's clogged, heat has nowhere to go — the drum temperature rises, clothes come out scorching, and the dryer either shuts off automatically or the thermal fuse blows. LG displays d80, d90, or d95 when sensors detect 80–95% airflow restriction. In Pasadena and Glendale where older homes often have longer vent runs with more bends, we find blockages more often than anywhere else. Quick check before you call: go outside while the dryer runs and feel the exterior vent cap. Weak or no airflow means clogged vent. We use calibrated temperature probes at multiple points in the exhaust path to confirm the restriction level and locate it precisely before we start clearing.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    2. Internal Lint Buildup Around the Heating Element
    <span class="sev-badge sev-mid">Common on older machines — fire hazard</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Burning smell that doesn't clear</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Persistent even after cleaning lint trap</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Often found alongside clogged vent</div>
  </div>
  <p>Lint that bypasses the lint trap accumulates inside the dryer cabinet — around the heating element housing, blower wheel, and exhaust ducting. This internal buildup does two things: it insulates the heating element so heat can't dissipate, and it's a fire hazard. A burning smell that doesn't clear after you clean the lint filter usually means internal lint is contacting the element. We find this on machines that haven't been serviced in years, especially in Beverly Hills and Malibu where dryers see high-usage loads. Cleaning internal lint is part of every overheating service call — a new thermal fuse in a machine packed with internal lint blows again quickly.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    3. Failed Cycling Thermostat
    <span class="sev-badge sev-mid">Vent is clear but still overheating</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Vent is clear but dryer still runs too hot</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Heat doesn't cycle off between bursts</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">tE1/tE2/tE3 error codes possible</div>
  </div>
  <p>The cycling thermostat regulates heat by turning the heating element on and off to maintain the correct drum temperature. When it fails in the "always on" position, the element runs continuously — no cycling, constant heat, temperatures that climb well above normal. The vent can be perfectly clear and the dryer will still overheat. LG displays tE1, tE2, or tE3 error codes when thermistor sensors detect dangerously high temperatures. Clothes come out scorched and the thermal fuse eventually blows from the sustained heat. We test the cycling thermostat on every overheating call where the vent is clear. Cost: $180–250 for thermostat replacement.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    4. Worn Drum Rollers Creating Mechanical Heat
    <span class="sev-badge sev-low">Less obvious but real</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Dryer runs hotter than normal under load</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Also squeaking or rumbling present</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Motor runs harder than it should</div>
  </div>
  <p>Worn <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-drum-roller-replacement/">drum rollers</a> create mechanical drag that forces the motor to work harder than designed. A motor under excessive load generates extra heat that gets into the drum space. On machines where we find severely worn rollers alongside a blown thermal fuse, this mechanical heat contribution is often part of the equation. We check roller condition on every overheating call while we're inside the machine.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    5. Heating Element Shorted to Ground (Electric Dryers)
    <span class="sev-badge sev-low">Less common</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Electric dryers only</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Runs too hot even on lowest setting</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Heat doesn't reduce when setting lowered</div>
  </div>
  <p>A heating element shorted to the chassis runs at full power regardless of what the thermostat signals — the thermostat can't cycle it off because the short bypasses the control circuit. Maximum heat on every setting, every cycle. We test element resistance and check for ground faults on every overheating call where the thermostat is good. See <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-heating-element-replacement/">heating element replacement</a>.</p>
</div>

<h2>When to Stop Using the Dryer Immediately</h2>
<p><strong>Burning smell</strong> — lint against the heating element or element failure. Fire risk. Stop the cycle now.</p>
<p><strong>Clothes with scorch marks or melted synthetics</strong> — drum temperature significantly above safe levels. Indicates complete heat regulation failure.</p>
<p><strong>Dryer shutting off mid-cycle repeatedly</strong> — thermal cutoff is tripping. Every trip brings you closer to the thermal fuse blowing permanently.</p>
<p><strong>d95 error code</strong> — 95% vent blockage. Don't run another cycle.</p>
<p><strong>tE1, tE2, tE3, tE4 codes</strong> — internal sensors detecting dangerous temperature levels. The dryer is entering protective shutdown. Don't restart it — call us.</p>

<h2>How to Prevent Overheating Going Forward</h2>
<p>Regular lint filter cleaning after every load is table stakes. Beyond that: check the exterior vent cap once a month while the dryer runs and confirm you feel strong airflow. Have the vent system professionally cleaned once a year if you run the dryer daily. Avoid overloading — a packed drum restricts airflow through the clothing and makes the machine work harder. And if you see a d80 or d90 code, treat it as urgent — don't wait for d95 or a blown fuse.</p>

