<h2>Questions We Get on These Calls</h2>

<h3>My LG dryer shuts off mid-cycle — is it overheating?</h3>
<p>Very likely yes. When the dryer's internal temperature exceeds the safe threshold, the thermal cutoff trips and stops the cycle. Almost always means the vent is restricted. Check airflow at the exterior vent cap while the dryer runs — weak or no flow confirms it. Call us before the thermal fuse blows permanently.</p>

<h3>My LG dryer shows d80 or d90 — what does that mean?</h3>
<p>80% or 90% airflow restriction in the exhaust vent. Stop running heated cycles — a fully blocked vent will blow the thermal fuse and turn your overheating problem into a no-heat problem on top of it. Call us to clear the vent and test airflow properly.</p>

<h3>My dryer smells like burning — what do I do?</h3>
<p>Stop the dryer immediately. A burning smell means either lint is contacting the heating element or the element is failing — both are fire risks. Don't run another cycle. Call us and describe the smell — fabric-burning smell points to lint, electrical burning smell points to element or wiring. Either way, stop using it.</p>

<h3>The vent looks clear but my LG dryer is still overheating. What else could it be?</h3>
<p>The cycling thermostat. It regulates heat by cycling the element on and off — when it fails stuck-on, the element runs at full power continuously regardless of the setting. Vent can be perfectly clear and the dryer still overheats. We test the thermostat on every overheating call where the vent is clean.</p>

<h3>How do I prevent my LG dryer from overheating again?</h3>
<p>Clean the lint filter every load. Check exterior vent airflow monthly. Have the vent professionally cleaned annually if you use the dryer daily. Don't overload. If you see d80 or d90, treat it as urgent — don't wait for d95 or a blown fuse. We'll give you specific maintenance guidance based on your installation when we're on-site.</p>

<h3>How do I know if my thermal fuse already blew from overheating?</h3>
<p>If the dryer is now completely dead or won't heat at all — but was running too hot before — the thermal fuse likely blew. No reset, has to be replaced. We confirm with a multimeter in minutes and fix the root cause (usually the vent) at the same visit. See our <a href="/symptoms/lg-dryer-not-heating/">LG dryer not heating</a> page.</p>

